    <h3 style="color: white; margin-top: 2rem; margin-bottom: 1rem;">Educational Deep Dive: The Evolution of Speech Synthesis</h3>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        How does a computer actually "speak"? In the early days, we used <strong>Concatenative Synthesis</strong>, which involved recording thousands of tiny sound clips from a human voice and stitching them together like a puzzle. This often sounded robotic and "choppy."
    </p>
    <p style="color: rgba(255,255,255,0.8); line-height: 1.6; margin-bottom: 1rem;">
        Modern Text-to-Speech (like the AI voices used by Webtigo) uses <strong>Neural Networks</strong>. Instead of stitching clips, the AI is trained on hundreds of hours of human speech to learn the nuances of tone, emotion, and rhythm. It then generates the audio from scratch, resulting in a voice that sounds incredibly natural and human-like.
    </p>

